Functions

These are functions from the ANOVA Tutorial

boxCoxNormalize <- function(x){
  if(length(x)<=1){
    x;
    }
    else{
        if(sum(x<=0)>0){
            x=x-min(x)+0.0001;
        }
        p=powerTransform(x)[6]$start;
        xnorm=(x^p -1)/p
        xnorm
    }
}

otu_tax_lev <- function(otu_table, TL){
  library('plyr')
  if(TL == 'species'){
    level <- 7
    }
    if(TL == 'genus'){
        level <- 6
    }
    if(TL == 'family'){
        level <- 5
    }
    if(TL == 'order'){
        level <- 4
    }
    if(TL == 'class'){
        level <- 3
    }
    if(TL == 'phylum'){
        level <- 2
    }
    if(TL == 'kingdom'){
        level <- 1
    }
    otu <- read.table(otu_table, comment='', header=T, sep="\t", as.is=TRUE, skip=1, check.names=F)
    otu <- otu[,-1]
    TAX <- length(otu[1,])
    LC <- length(otu[1,]) - 1
    otu <- otu[,c(TAX,1:LC)]
    otu[,2:TAX] <- lapply(otu[,2:TAX], as.numeric)
    names_split <- array(dim=c(length(otu$taxonomy), level))
    otu_names <- as.character(otu$taxonomy)
    otu_names <- as.matrix(otu_names)
    for (i in 1:nrow(otu_names)){
        names_split[i,] <- head(strsplit(otu_names[i], "; ", fixed=T)[[1]], n=level)
    }
    otu[,1] <- ldply(apply(names_split, 1, function(x) data.frame(x=paste(x[1:level], sep="", collapse="; "))))
    otu.m <- aggregate(otu[,2:ncol(otu)], by=list(otu$taxonomy), FUN=sum)
    rownames(otu.m) <- otu.m[,1]
    otuNames <- otu.m[,1]
    otu.m <- as.matrix(otu.m[,-1])
    return(list(otu_table = otu.m, otuNames = as.character(otuNames)))
}

Plot Significant OTUs

This is the final part of the tutorial

# This sets the margins and plotting parameters
plot.new()
par(mfrow=c(2,2))

# This loops through the significant taxa, removes the taxonomy delimiters and makes a box plot of the relative abundances of the taxa.
for(i in which(pvals.sex < 0.05)){
  y = as.numeric(otu.m[i,2:ncol(otu.m)])
  name1 = gsub('; .__',' ', as.character(otu.m[i,1]))
  name2 = gsub('k__','', name1)
  name3 = gsub('  ','', name2)
  name = strsplit(name3, " ", fixed=T)[[1]]
  names_tail = tail(name, n=2)
  boxplot(y ~ sex, main=names_tail, ylab="Relative abundance", col=c("tomato", "gray"), las=2)
}

Question #3

Question 3: If you filter out taxa that occur in fewer than 5 individuals (with no minimum percentage abundance): (A) How many taxa at the genus level differ significantly (p < 0.05) between body areas, body site, and sex? List one taxon that is significantly correlated with each variable (unless none are significant). (2 pt)

First we must reload the otu table, changing the taxa level to to genus.

In the code sample below (which is from above) we are only keeping taxa that occur in 4 or more individuals. To answer the question we must filter out (remove) taxa that occur in less than 5 individuals, so we must change the >= 4 accordingly. So if >= 4 is keeping taxa that occur in 4 or more individuals, we should change it to keep only taxa that occur in greater than 5 individuals (this filters out taxa that occur in fewer than 5). So change the cut-off below appropriately.

# reload taxa, changing TL to genus
otlOut <- otu_tax_lev('otu_rare2000.txt', TL='genus')

# Assign the otu table to the variable otu.m, and otu names to otuNames
otu.m <- otlOut$otu_table
otuNames <- otlOut$otuNames

# Change to relative abundance
for(i in 1:ncol(otu.m)){
  otu.m[,i] <- 100*otu.m[,i]/sum(otu.m[,i])
}

# Now we must change it to answer the question
cutoff <- rowSums(otu.m[,1:ncol(otu.m)] > 0) >= 4

# filter your OTU table based on that cutoff
otu.m <- otu.m[cutoff,]

# filter your otuNames based on that cutoff as well
otuNames <- otuNames[cutoff]

# Normalize the data with the boxCoxNormalize as before
for (i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  otu.m[i,] = boxCoxNormalize(otu.m[i,])
}

# Set the pvals vectors to empty
pvals.sex <- vector()
pvals.bs <- vector()
pvals.ba <- vector()

Question 3 continued….

Now we can re-run the ANOVA test, do the FDR corrections, and get out results

# This re-runs the ANOVA with our new cutoffs in place.
for(i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  y <- as.numeric(otu.m[i,])
  aovOut <- aov(y ~ sex)
  pvals.sex[i] <- summary(aovOut)[[1]][1,5]
}

for(i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  y <- as.numeric(otu.m[i,])
  aovOut <- aov(y ~ bs)
  pvals.bs[i] <- summary(aovOut)[[1]][1,5]
}

for(i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  y <- as.numeric(otu.m[i,])
  aovOut <- aov(y ~ ba)
  pvals.ba[i] <- summary(aovOut)[[1]][1,5]
}

# Re-do the FDR correction
pvals.sex = p.adjust(pvals.sex, "fdr")
pvals.bs = p.adjust(pvals.bs, "fdr")
pvals.ba = p.adjust(pvals.ba, "fdr")

# Now we can find how many are significant for each variable
sum(pvals.sex < 0.05)
## [1] 2
sum(pvals.bs < 0.05)
## [1] 143
sum(pvals.ba < 0.05)
## [1] 150

Question 5

For question 5 we would do similar to above, but we can choose a single variable. So we only need to re-use certain parts of the code.

# reload taxa, changing TL for each part of the question
otlOut <- otu_tax_lev('otu_rare2000.txt', TL='genus')

# Assign the otu table to the variable otu.m, and otu names to otuNames
otu.m <- otlOut$otu_table
otuNames <- otlOut$otuNames

# Change to relative abundance
for(i in 1:ncol(otu.m)){
  otu.m[,i] <- 100*otu.m[,i]/sum(otu.m[,i])
}

# Our cutoff is set for taxa that occur in 4 or more individuals
# BUT now we must change the minimum abundance to 0.1, which we can change at the 0 level
#cutoff <- rowSums(otu.m[,1:ncol(otu.m)] > 0) >= 4
cutoff <- rowSums(otu.m[,1:ncol(otu.m)] > 0.1) >= 4

otu.m <- otu.m[cutoff,]
otuNames <- otuNames[cutoff]

for (i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  otu.m[i,] = boxCoxNormalize(otu.m[i,])
}

# Let's only do bodyarea here...
pvals.ba <- vector()

for(i in 1:nrow(otu.m)){
  y <- as.numeric(otu.m[i,])
  aovOut <- aov(y ~ ba)
  pvals.ba[i] <- summary(aovOut)[[1]][1,5]
}

# Re-do the FDR correction
pvals.ba = p.adjust(pvals.ba, "fdr")

# Now we can find how many are significant for each variable
sum(pvals.ba < 0.05)
